{
  "What is the difference between energy efficiency and energy conservation?": "",
  "Efficiency applies only to industry; conservation applies only to homes": "",
  "Efficiency means using more energy; conservation means wasting energy": "",
  "Efficiency means using less energy to perform the same task; conservation means reducing energy use by changing behavior": "",
  "There is no difference; they are the same thing": "",
  "Energy efficiency involves performing the same function with less energy input (like LED bulbs producing the same light as incandescent bulbs with less electricity), while energy conservation means reducing overall energy use by changing behavior (like turning off lights).": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of improving energy efficiency?": "",
  "Turning off lights when leaving a room": "",
  "Riding a bicycle instead of driving": "",
  "Replacing an old refrigerator with an ENERGY STAR-rated model": "",
  "Taking shorter showers": "",
  "Replacing an old appliance with a more efficient model is energy efficiency because the new refrigerator performs the same function (keeping food cold) while using significantly less electricity; the other options are examples of energy conservation through behavior change.": "",
  "What is cogeneration (combined heat and power)?": "",
  "Combining solar and wind power in one facility": "",
  "Simultaneously producing electricity and useful heat from the same fuel source": "",
  "Using coal and gas together in the same power plant": "",
  "Generating electricity from two different renewable sources": "",
  "Cogeneration captures the waste heat from electricity generation and uses it for heating buildings or industrial processes, increasing the overall energy efficiency of the fuel from about 35% (electricity alone) to 80-90% (combined heat and power).": "",
  "Why is energy efficiency often called the 'first fuel' or the cheapest energy resource?": "",
  "Because all energy must be efficient by law": "",
  "Because it is the oldest form of energy": "",
  "Because reducing energy waste through efficiency is usually cheaper than producing new energy": "",
  "Because efficiency improvements are free": "",
  "Energy efficiency is called the 'first fuel' because investments in efficiency typically cost less per unit of energy saved than the cost of generating new energy, making it the most cost-effective way to meet energy needs and reduce emissions.": "",
  "What role does building insulation play in energy conservation?": "",
  "It only affects lighting energy consumption": "",
  "It increases the need for heating and cooling": "",
  "It reduces heat transfer, decreasing the energy needed for heating and cooling": "",
  "It has no effect on energy use": "",
  "Building insulation resists heat flow, keeping warm air inside during winter and outside during summer, which significantly reduces the energy needed for heating and cooling; space conditioning typically accounts for 40-50% of residential energy use.": "",
  "How much more efficient are LED light bulbs compared to traditional incandescent bulbs?": "",
  "Incandescent bulbs are more efficient than LEDs": "",
  "About 10% more efficient": "",
  "They use the same amount of energy": "",
  "About 75-80% more efficient": "",
  "LED bulbs use approximately 75-80% less electricity than incandescent bulbs to produce the same amount of light, and they last 15-25 times longer, making them one of the simplest and most impactful energy efficiency improvements available.": "",
  "What is the rebound effect in energy efficiency?": "",
  "The physical rebound of energy waves": "",
  "The phenomenon where efficiency gains lead to increased energy use because the saved money is spent on more energy-consuming activities": "",
  "The tendency for energy prices to bounce back after a decrease": "",
  "An increase in efficiency after initial investment": "",
  "The rebound effect occurs when efficiency improvements reduce the cost of using energy, which may encourage more use; for example, a more fuel-efficient car may lead someone to drive more, partially offsetting the energy savings.": "",
  "What is a green building certification like LEED?": "",
  "A rating system that certifies buildings meet standards for energy efficiency, water use, materials, and indoor environmental quality": "",
  "A building painted green on the exterior": "",
  "A requirement for buildings to use only solar energy": "",
  "A government permit to construct any type of building": "",
  "LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) is a globally recognized rating system that evaluates buildings on energy efficiency, water conservation, sustainable materials, indoor air quality, and other environmental criteria, promoting greener construction.": "",
  "What is a smart grid?": "",
  "A modernized electrical grid that uses digital technology to monitor and manage electricity flow efficiently": "",
  "A grid that operates without any human oversight": "",
  "A grid powered exclusively by artificial intelligence": "",
  "An electrical grid that only uses renewable energy": "",
  "A smart grid integrates digital communication technology, sensors, and automation into the electrical grid, enabling two-way information flow between utilities and consumers, optimizing electricity distribution, integrating renewable energy, and improving reliability and efficiency.": "",
  "What is the CAFE (Corporate Average Fuel Economy) standard?": "",
  "A certification for cafeteria food quality": "",
  "A voluntary guideline for corporate office energy use": "",
  "U.S. federal regulations that set minimum fuel efficiency requirements for automobiles": "",
  "A standard for coffee shop energy use": "",
  "CAFE standards are U.S. federal regulations that mandate minimum average fuel economy levels for new passenger cars and light trucks sold in the United States, pushing automakers to improve vehicle efficiency and reduce fuel consumption and emissions.": "",
  "What does 'energy efficiency' mean?": "",
  "Generating energy from renewable sources": "",
  "The total amount of energy a country produces": "",
  "The ratio of useful energy output to total energy input, or performing the same function with less energy": "",
  "Using as much energy as possible to accomplish a task": "",
  "Energy efficiency is the ratio of useful energy output to total energy input; improving efficiency means getting the same service (lighting, heating, transportation) while using less energy, reducing waste, costs, and environmental impact.": "",
  "What does 'energy conservation' mean?": "",
  "Maintaining energy levels in the human body": "",
  "Conserving fossil fuel reserves by finding new deposits": "",
  "Reducing overall energy consumption through changes in behavior or practices": "",
  "Storing energy in batteries for future use": "",
  "Energy conservation is the practice of using less energy overall by making behavioral changes or reducing energy-consuming activities, such as turning off lights, driving less, lowering thermostats, or air-drying clothes.": "",
  "What is a 'carbon footprint'?": "",
  "The physical footprint of a carbon-producing factory": "",
  "The amount of carbon stored in soil": "",
  "The total amount of greenhouse gases emitted directly and indirectly by an individual, organization, event, or product": "",
  "A fossil footprint preserved in coal": "",
  "A carbon footprint measures the total greenhouse gas emissions (expressed in CO2 equivalents) caused by an individual, organization, event, or product, encompassing both direct emissions and indirect emissions from the energy used throughout the supply chain.": "",
  "What does 'R-value' mean in building construction?": "",
  "The rental value of a property": "",
  "A measure of a material's resistance to heat flow, with higher values indicating better insulation": "",
  "The rate of energy consumption per room": "",
  "The reflectivity of roof materials": "",
  "R-value measures thermal resistance, indicating how well a material resists heat flow; higher R-values mean better insulation performance. Recommended R-values vary by climate zone and building component (walls, attic, floors).": "",
  "What does 'energy audit' mean?": "",
  "An assessment of a building's energy use to identify opportunities for reducing consumption and improving efficiency": "",
  "A government inspection of power plant safety": "",
  "A test of battery capacity in electronic devices": "",
  "A financial audit of an energy company's profits": "",
  "An energy audit systematically evaluates how energy is used in a building or facility, identifies areas of waste and inefficiency, and recommends improvements such as better insulation, upgraded equipment, or behavioral changes to reduce energy consumption and costs.": "",
  "What is meant by 'thermal mass' in building design?": "",
  "The weight of heating equipment in a building": "",
  "The total mass of a building's structure": "",
  "A material's ability to absorb, store, and slowly release heat, helping to moderate indoor temperature swings": "",
  "The amount of heat generated by the building's occupants": "",
  "Thermal mass refers to dense materials (like concrete, brick, or stone) that absorb and store heat during the day and slowly release it at night, helping to moderate indoor temperature fluctuations and reduce the need for active heating and cooling.": "",
  "What does 'phantom load' or 'standby power' mean?": "",
  "The maximum power a device can draw": "",
  "Electricity consumed by electronic devices while they are turned off but still plugged in": "",
  "Electricity used by haunted houses": "",
  "The power used by emergency backup generators": "",
  "Phantom load (standby power or vampire power) is the electricity consumed by devices that are plugged in but not actively in use, including chargers, TVs in standby mode, and appliances with displays; collectively, phantom loads can account for 5-10% of household electricity use.": "",
  "What does 'net-zero energy building' mean?": "",
  "A building that produces as much energy as it consumes over the course of a year": "",
  "A building with zero construction costs": "",
  "A building that uses no energy whatsoever": "",
  "A building made entirely from recycled materials": "",
  "A net-zero energy building is designed to generate as much energy as it uses annually through on-site renewable energy production (typically solar), combined with high energy efficiency to minimize overall consumption.": "",
  "What does 'demand-side management' mean in energy policy?": "",
  "Increasing energy supply to meet growing demand": "",
  "Managing how much energy power plants demand from fuel suppliers": "",
  "Demanding that consumers pay higher prices for energy": "",
  "Programs and policies that influence consumer energy use patterns to reduce demand, especially during peak periods": "",
  "Demand-side management includes utility programs and policies that encourage consumers to modify their energy use patterns, including efficiency improvements, time-of-use pricing, peak shaving, and behavioral programs to reduce overall consumption and shift demand away from peak hours.": "",
  "What is 'fuel economy'?": "",
  "The total fuel production of a country": "",
  "The distance a vehicle can travel per unit of fuel consumed, such as miles per gallon": "",
  "The economy of countries that produce fuel": "",
  "The cost of fuel per gallon": "",
  "Fuel economy measures how efficiently a vehicle uses fuel, expressed as the distance traveled per unit of fuel (miles per gallon or liters per 100 km); higher fuel economy means the vehicle uses less fuel to travel the same distance.": "",
  "Japan's Top Runner program sets efficiency standards for appliances and equipment based on the most efficient product currently on the market, then requires all manufacturers to meet that standard within a specified time period. How does this approach differ from traditional minimum efficiency standards?": "",
  "It only applies to a single appliance category": "",
  "It is identical to traditional minimum standards": "",
  "It continuously ratchets up efficiency requirements based on the best available technology, driving continuous innovation rather than setting a static floor": "",
  "It allows manufacturers to produce any efficiency level they choose": "",
  "The Top Runner approach is dynamic: the most efficient product sets the benchmark, and all products must reach that level within a deadline; when the deadline passes, the new best product sets the next benchmark, creating a continuous cycle of improvement.": "",
  "A study finds that buildings account for approximately 40% of total energy consumption in the United States. Of this, about 30% is wasted due to poor insulation, inefficient equipment, and energy-wasting behavior. A policy maker proposes mandatory energy efficiency retrofits for all existing buildings. What challenge makes this policy difficult to implement?": "",
  "Buildings do not consume energy given that the interplay between building forces and related energy mechanisms determines behavior over extended periods": "",
  "Energy efficiency retrofits increase energy consumption, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing building dynamics": "",
  "Building retrofits have no energy savings potential given that prevailing building conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "The high upfront cost of retrofits, split incentives between building owners and tenants, and the vast number of existing buildings make comprehensive retrofitting logistically and financially challenging": "",
  "Building retrofits face multiple barriers: high upfront costs that deter investment, the split incentive problem (landlords pay for improvements but tenants receive lower utility bills), the enormous scale of the existing building stock, and varying building types and conditions.": "",
  "A city implements a congestion pricing program that charges drivers a fee to enter the downtown core during peak hours. Traffic decreases by 20% and public transit ridership increases by 15%. What energy and environmental benefits does this program provide?": "",
  "Congestion pricing has no environmental benefits": "",
  "Reduced traffic decreases fuel consumption, vehicle emissions, and air pollution while encouraging more energy-efficient public transit use": "",
  "The program only benefits the government through revenue": "",
  "Congestion pricing increases traffic and pollution": "",
  "Congestion pricing reduces vehicle miles traveled, which directly decreases fuel consumption and tailpipe emissions; the shift to public transit further reduces per-person energy use, and less congestion means remaining vehicles operate more efficiently with less stop-and-go driving.": "",
  "A manufacturer replaces an old electric motor system with a high-efficiency variable speed drive motor. The new motor uses 30% less electricity while maintaining the same production output. The payback period is 18 months. Why might some companies still resist making this investment?": "",
  "Efficient motors produce lower quality products, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Companies may prioritize short-term capital allocation, lack information about efficiency opportunities, or focus on core production rather than energy management": "",
  "The investment would never pay for itself, since standard models of motor behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Variable speed drives increase energy consumption, particularly in the context of motor": "",
  "Despite excellent financial returns, the 'energy efficiency gap' persists because companies face competing capital priorities, may lack technical expertise, have limited information about opportunities, focus on core business rather than utilities, or have organizational inertia that discourages change.": "",
  "Electric vehicles (EVs) convert about 77% of electrical energy from the grid to power at the wheels, while conventional gasoline cars convert only about 12-30% of the fuel's energy to power at the wheels. What does this efficiency difference mean for total energy consumption and emissions?": "",
  "The efficiency difference has no effect on total energy use": "",
  "EVs are less efficient because they require electricity": "",
  "Gasoline cars are more energy efficient than EVs": "",
  "EVs require significantly less total energy per mile and produce lower lifecycle emissions, especially when charged from clean electricity sources": "",
  "EVs' much higher drivetrain efficiency means they need roughly one-third the total energy of gasoline cars per mile driven; when powered by renewable electricity, their lifecycle emissions are dramatically lower, and even with fossil-fuel-generated electricity, they typically produce fewer emissions.": "",
  "A family installs a smart thermostat that learns their schedule, adjusts temperature automatically when they are away, and can be controlled remotely. Their heating and cooling costs drop by 23%. This is an example of how digital technology supports energy efficiency. What broader trend does this represent?": "",
  "Smart technology and the Internet of Things can optimize energy use by automating efficiency improvements that people would not consistently make manually": "",
  "Technology always increases energy consumption": "",
  "Digital technology has no role in energy management": "",
  "Smart thermostats increase energy use by keeping homes too comfortable": "",
  "Smart home technology represents the broader trend of using digital intelligence to optimize energy use: sensors, data analytics, and automation can identify and eliminate waste that humans would miss, continuously adjusting systems for optimal efficiency without requiring constant attention.": "",
  "A developing country faces the dual challenge of expanding energy access for its population while limiting greenhouse gas emissions. International organizations recommend 'leapfrogging' directly to efficient technologies rather than following the path of developed nations. What does 'leapfrogging' mean in this context?": "",
  "Copying the exact development path of wealthy nations": "",
  "Skipping energy infrastructure entirely": "",
  "Using only traditional energy sources like wood": "",
  "Bypassing older, inefficient technologies and adopting the most efficient modern technologies from the start": "",
  "Leapfrogging means skipping intermediate inefficient technologies; for example, adopting LED lighting instead of first using incandescent then fluorescent, or deploying solar microgrids instead of building coal plants, allowing developing nations to grow sustainably from the start.": "",
  "A city's public transit agency replaces its aging diesel bus fleet with electric buses. The electric buses cost more upfront but have lower fuel and maintenance costs. After 12 years of operation, the total cost of ownership is 15% less than diesel. What makes electric buses more economical over their lifetime despite higher purchase prices?": "",
  "Electric buses never need any maintenance, particularly when buses considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "Electricity is cheaper per mile than diesel, electric motors have fewer moving parts requiring less maintenance, and regenerative braking reduces brake wear": "",
  "Electric buses are always cheaper to purchase than diesel buses under most circumstances involving buses": "",
  "The government pays for all electric bus fuel costs, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Electric buses benefit from lower fuel costs (electricity is cheaper than diesel per mile), simpler drivetrains with fewer moving parts (reducing maintenance costs), regenerative braking that extends brake life, and no oil changes, making total cost of ownership favorable despite higher purchase prices.": "",
  "An industrial facility wastes 65% of the energy it consumes as heat that is released into the environment through exhaust gases and cooling water. An energy consultant proposes a waste heat recovery system. What is the environmental significance of capturing and using this waste heat?": "",
  "Waste heat has no value and cannot be recovered when considering all relevant energy factors": "",
  "Waste heat recovery increases total energy consumption within the broader context of energy analysis": "",
  "Recovering waste heat reduces the need for additional fuel, lowering energy costs and greenhouse gas emissions without requiring additional resource extraction": "",
  "Industrial facilities are already 100% efficient regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Waste heat recovery captures thermal energy that would otherwise be lost and uses it for process heating, building heating, or electricity generation; this reduces total fuel consumption and emissions because less new energy needs to be produced to meet the same energy demands.": "",
  "California's energy efficiency policies have kept per-capita electricity consumption flat since the 1970s, while national per-capita consumption increased by 50% over the same period. California's economy continued to grow robustly during this time. What does California's experience demonstrate about the relationship between energy use and economic growth?": "",
  "California's economy did not grow during this period": "",
  "Strong efficiency policies can decouple economic growth from energy consumption, enabling prosperity with stable or declining energy use": "",
  "Economic growth always requires proportional increases in energy consumption": "",
  "Energy efficiency has no effect on per-capita consumption": "",
  "California demonstrates that the historical link between economic growth and energy consumption can be broken through aggressive efficiency policies, building codes, appliance standards, and utility programs, proving that prosperity and reduced energy intensity are compatible.": ""
